811 is a 40sqm workspace designed using the 100-year-old reclaimed Teak Wood salvaged
from demolished structures of Old Bombay built during the British Era.
Striving for the balance of form, function and simplicity, we adopted an open layout while
working with natural materials and unconfined natural light. We leaned towards the Japandi
aesthetic as it matched perfectly with our objectives of minimalism and Practical Sustainability.
We were squarely aware of the insurmountable charge of shunning the ornate, retaining the
essentials whilst maintaining warmth and comfort. We took smaller steps towards the enduring
and compounding changes possible with our material choices.

The initial design plan shared with us didnâ€™t align with our vision due to placement issues within the rooms. We saw this as an opportunity to improve the flow of the home. Upon being introduced to the project after the foundational columns and plinth beams were already constructed, we took it as an opportunity to enhance the design with minimal structural changes. Our goal was to create a more open layout that fosters interaction from every corner of the house. By incorporating a central double-height space, we maximized daylight throughout the home, ensuring a bright and inviting atmosphere. The master bedroom is thoughtfully positioned to face east, featuring a terrace that offers stunning, unobstructed views of the surrounding paddy fields. The kitchen has a seamless connection to the backyard garden, while the utilities are strategically tucked away in one corner, allowing for a clean, unobstructed living-dining-kitchen layout. The front verandah elegantly links the interior to the beautifully landscaped outdoor space, enhancing the overall connection to the breathtaking paddy fields ahead. Additionally, the media room is designed to serve as an extra living space when needed, cleverly connected to the lower floor living and dining areas. This arrangement creates an emotional bond throughout the home, making it a truly inviting and cohesive living environment.

Stepping away from the hustle of the city, Sakura Home aims to be a mental switch-off space. The home stands as a testament to the fusion of design innovation and the pursuit of tranquillity. 

When our client approached us to redesign their home, their pivotal grievance was that despite the available floor space, the house always felt anything but spacious.

When we set off to design a more welcoming abode, a couple of internal walls were demolished to usher in the natural light that bathed the entire home with positivity.

With a rough east-west axis, the living room strategically opens to the south, flooding the space with natural light. We enlarged the windows embracing the south-facing aspect, creating a space where the family can gather, relax, and work in perfect harmony with the surroundings.

We chose a neutral palette that permeates the interiors, providing a canvas that allows its residents to savour the peaceful aesthetic. The design philosophy focuses on creating focal points within the space, relinquishing superfluous features for a more coherent environment.

Striving for the balance of form, function and simplicity, we adopted an open kitchen layout while working with natural materials and unconfined natural light. We leaned towards the Japandi aesthetic as it matched perfectly with our objectives of minimalism and Practical Sustainability. 

Navigating the creation of a Japandi-inspired dwelling, we understood the significant task of steering clear of excessive embellishments. We aimed to hold onto the fundamentals while ensuring a cosy and inviting atmosphere. We opted for a pragmatic approach, taking measured steps in our choice of materials, and acknowledging the lasting transformations that small decisions can engender.

In a city home, making changes to the layout can be quite challenging due to tight designs that leave little room for adjustments. When the client approached us, they had specific concerns that needed addressing. Based on Vastu principles, it was essential to relocate the toilet away from the northeast side of the home. Additionally, the kitchen's limited space posed a problem for accommodating the client's newly purchased 650-litre refrigerator. We expertly navigated these Vastu issues while optimising the best locations for utilities, ensuring that the balcony remained unobstructed by outdoor AC units. Our solution involved slightly encroaching into the dining area to make room for the fridge, while maintaining an open layout and a spacious feel, free from unnecessary obstacles. The result is a Vastu-compliant home that fosters a positive environment for its occupants. A standout feature of this residence is the impressive 50-foot-wide balcony that runs along the length of the home, seamlessly connecting all areas. With lush greenery just outside, this space invites nature in, making it impossible to leave once you sit down and relax.

The breathtaking view of Lake Arthur is mesmerizing. Witnessing the sun set over the water is one of the most soothing experiences, one you can never tire of. A site like this deserves a structure that embodies simplicity, free from obstructions. By harnessing the natural slope of the land, we created a stacked design instead of a traditional block frame. Itâ€™s crucial that utilities do not dominate the view, so we zoned them thoughtfully, allowing the open staircase to shine as a stunning vertical feature. The west-facing glass offers a clear perspective, yet it can make the space uncomfortable during the summer midday heat. To overcome this challenge, we designed a roof overhang to elegantly block direct sunlight. Openings enhance a wind-driven design, controlling airflow and ensuring cool surfaces at all times. Our goal is to create a space that prioritizes comfort; after all, an uncomfortable environment can never be truly calming. Surrounded by nature on all sides, this house stands as a sanctuary of silenceâ€”a perfect haven for those seeking a serene and peaceful existence.
